Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
write_metric(25.10)                                        write_metric(25.10)

Name
       write_metric - Writes the current set of metrics to a file or stdout

Syntax
       write_metric

       [<pattern>]

       [-format <output_format>]

       [-id <metric_id>]

       [-merge]

       [-names <list_of_patterns>]

       [-out_file <fileName>]

       Writes the current set of metrics to a file or stdout.

       The  write_metric  command  is used by write_db to write the metrics in
       the  JSON  format  in  the  database  directory.  Super  commands   use
       write_metric to write metrics into the log file (stdout). This can also
       be used to write metrics in various formats by the user.

Parameters
       -format <output_format>
              Specifies the output format, json, xml, csv, tcl.

              Default: JSON

              Data_type: string, optional

       -help  Outputs  a  brief description that includes type and default in-
              formation for each write_metric parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man write_metric

       <-id metric_id >
              Specifies a list of labels from read_metrics.

              Default: Current metric

              Data_type: string, optional

       -merge Merges the results into an existing file.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -names  <list_of_patterns>
              Specifies the list of patterns to match snapshot names.

              Data_type: string, optional

       <pattern>
              List of regular expressions to chose metrics to  write.  Default
              is all metrics (*).

              Data_type: string, optional

       -out_file <fileName>
              Specifies the name of the file in which metrics is written.

              Data_type: string, optional

Example
       The following code shows the usage of the write_metric command:

       # --------------------------------------------------------------------

       # Generate a XML file for all timing, power, and flow metrics from

       # from prects to postcts for a previous run (id v101)

       # --------------------------------------------------------------------

       read_metric -id v101 run101/dbs/postcts.enc.dat/design.metrics

       write_metric -id v101 -format xml

